<paragraph blockId="2.[159,1156,1320,1726]" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675">
The semi-terrestrial shrimp 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Estuarine" baseAuthorityName="Rathbun" baseAuthorityYear="1900" box="[460,620,1320,1345]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Merguia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rhizophorae">
<emphasis box="[460,620,1320,1345]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675">M. rhizophorae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was originally described in the state of 
<collectingRegion box="[1064,1152,1320,1345]" country="Brazil" name="Alagoas" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675">Alagoas</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[159,217,1354,1379]" name="Brazil" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Rathbun MJ" box="[232,388,1354,1379]" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675" pagination="133 - 156" refId="ref9741" refString="Rathbun MJ. 1900. Results of the Branner-Agassiz expedition to Brazil. I. The decapod and stomatopod Crustacea. Proc Washingt Acad Sci. 2: 133 - 156." type="journal article" year="1900">Rathbun 1900</bibRefCitation>
). Since then, other studies have shown that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Estuarine" baseAuthorityName="Rathbun" baseAuthorityYear="1900" box="[889,1050,1354,1379]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Merguia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rhizophorae">
<emphasis box="[889,1050,1354,1379]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675">M. rhizophorae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is widely distributed in tropical Western Atlantic, 
<collectingCountry box="[603,693,1389,1414]" name="Panama" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675">Panama</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[705,810,1389,1414]" name="Suriname" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675">Suriname</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[873,931,1389,1414]" name="Brazil" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[947,1033,1389,1414]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="3.[160,225,1292,1315]" captionTargetBox="[164,1151,144,1258]" captionTargetId="figure-78@3.[163,1153,142,1260]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 1. (a) Occurrence of Merguia rhizophorae along the western Atlantic. The red circle shows Vaza- Barris estuarine region of Sergipe State, northeastern coast of Brazil and blue circle shows the previous records of the species (obtained from literature and Global Biodiversity Information Facility – GBIF; http://www.gbif.org); (b–c) Sampling site in a fringe mangrove forest; (d) Excavation of the burrows using a spatula; (e) Burrows (white arrows) inhabited by mud shrimps (yellow arrow) distributed on the sediment of the intertidal zone; (f) lateral view of Merguia rhizophorae (Rathbun 1900). Photo credits: Douglas F.R. Alves." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6000843" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6000843/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675">Figure 1</figureCitation>
(a)) (
<bibRefCitation author="Chace FA Jr." pageId="2" pageNumber="2675" pagination="1 - 191" refId="ref8189" refString="Chace FA Jr. 1972. The shrimps of the Smithsonian-Bredin Caribbean expeditions with a summary of the West Indian shallow-water species (Crustacea: Decapoda: Natantia). Smithson Contrib to Zool. 98: 1 - 191." type="journal article" year="1972">Chace 1972</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Almeida AO &amp; Coelho PA &amp; Santos JTA &amp; Ferraz NR" box="[225,434,1424,1449]" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675" pagination="1 - 24" refId="ref7105" refString="Almeida AO, Coelho PA, Santos JTA, Ferraz NR. 2006. Crustaceos decapodos estuarinos de Ilheus, Bahia, Brasil. Biota Neotrop. 6: 1 - 24. doi: 10.1590 / S 1676 - 06032006000200024." type="journal article" year="2006">Almeida et al. 2006</bibRefCitation>
). In this study, shrimps were collected in the estuary region of the Vaza-Barris River (
<geoCoordinate box="[351,466,1458,1483]" degrees="11" direction="south" minutes="05" orientation="latitude" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675" precision="15" seconds="47" value="-11.096389">
11°05 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[413,418,1459,1482]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675">ʹ</emphasis>
47”S
</geoCoordinate>
– 
<geoCoordinate box="[494,622,1458,1483]" degrees="37" direction="west" minutes="09" orientation="longitude" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675" precision="15" seconds="30" value="-37.158337">
37°09 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[555,560,1459,1482]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675">ʹ</emphasis>
30”W
</geoCoordinate>
), 
<collectingRegion box="[637,781,1458,1483]" country="Brazil" name="Sergipe" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675">Sergipe state</collectingRegion>
, northeast 
<collectingCountry box="[901,959,1458,1483]" name="Brazil" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[974,1057,1458,1483]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="3.[160,225,1292,1315]" captionTargetBox="[164,1151,144,1258]" captionTargetId="figure-78@3.[163,1153,142,1260]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 1. (a) Occurrence of Merguia rhizophorae along the western Atlantic. The red circle shows Vaza- Barris estuarine region of Sergipe State, northeastern coast of Brazil and blue circle shows the previous records of the species (obtained from literature and Global Biodiversity Information Facility – GBIF; http://www.gbif.org); (b–c) Sampling site in a fringe mangrove forest; (d) Excavation of the burrows using a spatula; (e) Burrows (white arrows) inhabited by mud shrimps (yellow arrow) distributed on the sediment of the intertidal zone; (f) lateral view of Merguia rhizophorae (Rathbun 1900). Photo credits: Douglas F.R. Alves." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6000843" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6000843/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675">Figure 1</figureCitation>
(a–e)). In this region of 
<collectingCountry box="[322,382,1493,1518]" name="Brazil" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, mangrove forests are commonly observed in the estuarine regions, composed mainly of 
<taxonomicName box="[389,595,1528,1553]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rhizophoraceae" genus="Rhizophora" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mangle">
<emphasis box="[389,595,1528,1553]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675">Rhizophora mangle</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L., 
<taxonomicName box="[632,877,1528,1553]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Combretaceae" genus="Laguncularia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="racemosa">
<emphasis box="[632,877,1528,1553]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675">Laguncularia racemosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(L.) C.F. Gaertn, 
<taxonomicName authority="Stapf &amp; Leechman ex Moldenke" authorityName="Moldenke" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" genus="Avicennia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="schaueriana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675">Avicennia schaueriana</emphasis>
Stapf &amp; Leechman ex Moldenke
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[684,902,1562,1587]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" genus="Avicennia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="germinans">
<emphasis box="[684,902,1562,1587]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675">Avicennia germinans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(L.) Stearn (
<bibRefCitation author="Santos TO &amp; Andrade KVS &amp; Santos HVS &amp; Castaneda DAFG &amp; Santana MBS &amp; Holanda FSR &amp; Santos MJC" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675" pagination="1 - 7" refId="ref9871" refString="Santos TO, Andrade KVS, Santos HVS, Castaneda DAFG, Santana MBS, Holanda FSR, Santos MJC. 2012. Caracterizacao estrutural de bosques de mangue: Estuario do Sao Francisco. Sci Plena. 8 (4): 1 - 7." type="journal article" year="2012">Santos et al. 2012</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[159,1156,1320,1726]" lastBlockId="4.[160,1155,142,549]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="2677" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675">
During a sampling of 
<taxonomicName authority="Gomes Correa, 1968" authorityName="Gomes Correa" authorityYear="1968" box="[434,854,1632,1657]" class="Malacostraca" family="Upogebiidae" genus="Upogebia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="omissa">
<emphasis box="[434,621,1632,1657]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675">Upogebia omissa</emphasis>
Gomes Corrêa, 1968
</taxonomicName>
carried out previously (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Santos RDC &amp; Silva LF &amp; Santos B &amp; Motta JM &amp; Alves DFR" box="[160,373,1666,1691]" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675" pagination="95 - 104" refId="ref9800" refString="Santos RDC, Silva LF, Santos B, Motta JM, Alves DFR. 2018. Population structure and fecundity of Upogebia omissa (Decapoda: Gebiidea: Upogebiidae) in an estuarine region in Sergipe, northeastern Brazil. Pesquisa E Ensino Em Ciencias Exatas E Da Natureza. 2 (2): 95 - 104. doi: 10.29215 / pecen. v 2 i 2.1064." type="journal article" year="2018">Santos et al. 2018</bibRefCitation>
), specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Estuarine" baseAuthorityName="Rathbun" baseAuthorityYear="1900" box="[564,734,1666,1691]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Merguia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rhizophorae">
<emphasis box="[564,734,1666,1691]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="2675">M. rhizophorae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were observed cohabiting burrows constructed by mud shrimps. Thus, the sampling sites in the present study were selected based on occurrence of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gomes Correa" authorityYear="1968" box="[452,562,1565,1590]" class="Malacostraca" family="Upogebiidae" genus="Upogebia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="2676" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="omissa">
<emphasis box="[452,562,1565,1590]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2676">U. omissa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
burrows along the fringe of the mangrove forest (
<figureCitation box="[168,255,1599,1624]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="3.[160,225,1292,1315]" captionTargetBox="[164,1151,144,1258]" captionTargetId="figure-78@3.[163,1153,142,1260]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 1. (a) Occurrence of Merguia rhizophorae along the western Atlantic. The red circle shows Vaza- Barris estuarine region of Sergipe State, northeastern coast of Brazil and blue circle shows the previous records of the species (obtained from literature and Global Biodiversity Information Facility – GBIF; http://www.gbif.org); (b–c) Sampling site in a fringe mangrove forest; (d) Excavation of the burrows using a spatula; (e) Burrows (white arrows) inhabited by mud shrimps (yellow arrow) distributed on the sediment of the intertidal zone; (f) lateral view of Merguia rhizophorae (Rathbun 1900). Photo credits: Douglas F.R. Alves." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6000843" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6000843/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="2676">Figure 1</figureCitation>
(b–e)). During daytime samplings at low tide, in places where a dense concentration of burrows was observed (
<figureCitation box="[568,660,1634,1659]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="3.[160,225,1292,1315]" captionTargetBox="[164,1151,144,1258]" captionTargetId="figure-78@3.[163,1153,142,1260]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 1. (a) Occurrence of Merguia rhizophorae along the western Atlantic. The red circle shows Vaza- Barris estuarine region of Sergipe State, northeastern coast of Brazil and blue circle shows the previous records of the species (obtained from literature and Global Biodiversity Information Facility – GBIF; http://www.gbif.org); (b–c) Sampling site in a fringe mangrove forest; (d) Excavation of the burrows using a spatula; (e) Burrows (white arrows) inhabited by mud shrimps (yellow arrow) distributed on the sediment of the intertidal zone; (f) lateral view of Merguia rhizophorae (Rathbun 1900). Photo credits: Douglas F.R. Alves." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6000843" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6000843/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="2676">Figure 1</figureCitation>
(c–e)), the sediment around burrows was manually excavated (or using a spatula) (Figure D) and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Estuarine" baseAuthorityName="Rathbun" baseAuthorityYear="1900" box="[781,945,1669,1694]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Merguia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="2676" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rhizophorae">
<emphasis box="[781,945,1669,1694]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2676">M. rhizophorae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[960,1048,1669,1694]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="3.[160,225,1292,1315]" captionTargetBox="[164,1151,144,1258]" captionTargetId="figure-78@3.[163,1153,142,1260]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 1. (a) Occurrence of Merguia rhizophorae along the western Atlantic. The red circle shows Vaza- Barris estuarine region of Sergipe State, northeastern coast of Brazil and blue circle shows the previous records of the species (obtained from literature and Global Biodiversity Information Facility – GBIF; http://www.gbif.org); (b–c) Sampling site in a fringe mangrove forest; (d) Excavation of the burrows using a spatula; (e) Burrows (white arrows) inhabited by mud shrimps (yellow arrow) distributed on the sediment of the intertidal zone; (f) lateral view of Merguia rhizophorae (Rathbun 1900). Photo credits: Douglas F.R. Alves." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6000843" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6000843/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="2676">Figure 1</figureCitation>
(f)) specimens were captured. All shrimps were captured in burrows inhabited by mud shrimps 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gomes Correa" authorityYear="1968" box="[160,263,142,167]" class="Malacostraca" family="Upogebiidae" genus="Upogebia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="4" pageNumber="2677" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="omissa">
<emphasis box="[160,263,142,167]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="2677">U. omissa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, considering the large number of burrows in the substratum and their structural complexity (commonly ‘Y-shaped’ and possible connections with neighbouring burrows, see 
<bibRefCitation author="Coelho VR &amp; Cooper RA &amp; Rodrigues AS" box="[307,507,212,237]" pageId="4" pageNumber="2677" pagination="229 - 240" refId="ref8433" refString="Coelho VR, Cooper RA, Rodrigues AS. 2000. Burrow morphology and behavior of the mud shrimp Ubogenia omissa (Decapoda: Thalassinidea: Upogebiidae). Mar Ecol Prog Ser. 200: 229 - 240. doi: 10.3354 / meps 200229." type="book chapter" year="2000">Coelho et al. 2000</bibRefCitation>
), it was not possible to verify (1) whether all burrows were inhabited by individuals of both species (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Estuarine" baseAuthorityName="Rathbun" baseAuthorityYear="1900" box="[618,781,246,271]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Merguia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="4" pageNumber="2677" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rhizophorae">
<emphasis box="[618,781,246,271]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="2677">M. rhizophorae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gomes Correa" authorityYear="1968" box="[836,940,246,271]" class="Malacostraca" family="Upogebiidae" genus="Upogebia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="4" pageNumber="2677" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="omissa">
<emphasis box="[836,940,246,271]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="2677">U. omissa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), (2) the number of shrimps of each species per burrow, (3) if there were burrows of other crustaceans that were also occupied by 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Estuarine" baseAuthorityName="Rathbun" baseAuthorityYear="1900" box="[420,584,316,341]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Merguia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="4" pageNumber="2677" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rhizophorae">
<emphasis box="[420,584,316,341]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="2677">M. rhizophorae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
individuals.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6000843" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6000843" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6000843/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="2676" startId="3.[160,225,1292,1315]" targetBox="[164,1151,144,1258]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph blockId="3.[160,1157,1292,1491]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2676">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,249,1292,1315]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2676">Figure 1.</emphasis>
(a) Occurrence of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Estuarine" baseAuthorityName="Rathbun" baseAuthorityYear="1900" box="[427,625,1292,1315]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Merguia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="2676" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rhizophorae">
<emphasis box="[427,625,1292,1315]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2676">Merguia rhizophorae</emphasis>
